# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: barring-engine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:barring-engine/barring-engine] A **barring engine** (also called **barring motor**) is a small engine that forms part of the installation of a large engine, and is used to turn the main engine to a favourable position from which it can be started.
[src:barring-engine/barring-engine] If the main engine has stopped close to its dead centre it is unable to restart itself.
[src:barring-engine/barring-engine] Barring may also be done to turn the engine over slowly (unloaded) for maintenance, or to prevent belt drives being left too long in one position and taking a "set".
[src:barring-engine/barring-engine] Originally they were used to turn stationary steam engines to a position from which they could be started.
[src:barring-engine/barring-engine] These early barring engines were themselves small steam engines.
[src:barring-engine/barring-engine] Today they are found on most large marine vessels, such as supertankers and container ships, and are driven by compressed air.
[src:barring-engine/barring-engine] For modern large scale power plant, after a generation unit has been shut down, the shaft line and casing is gradually cooled, where cooling might not be even for the upper and lower side of the shaft.
[src:barring-engine/barring-engine] The uneven cooling may cause bending to the shaft, ultimately leading to vibrations and unbalanced output.
[src:barring-engine/barring-engine] The barring gear will rotate the shaft at a low speed, typically 5rpm, until the shaft is completely cooled down, to avoid the above situation.
[src:barring-engine/barring-engine] The first barring engines or *barring gear* were manual.
[src:barring-engine/barring-engine] At their simplest, they were a hefty engineer with a crowbar (hence the term "barring").
[src:barring-engine/barring-engine] The engine's flywheel could be provided with a series of holes or teeth and a roller fulcrum set into the frame at a convenient place.
[src:barring-engine/barring-engine] Later manual barring engines had geared drives and a crank handle.
[src:barring-engine/barring-engine] With suitable reduction gears, even very large engines could be barred by hand.
[src:barring-engine/barring-engine] This only needed to be done once a day and was not a hurried operation, so speed was not crucial.
[src:barring-engine/barring-engine] Where a steam barring engine was used, this was a small twin-cylinder engine (to avoid its own dead centre problems) with a reduction gear of high ratio, usually involving a worm gear.
[src:barring-engine/barring-engine] Final drive was by a pinion gear engaging temporarily with the teeth or barring holes cut into the rim of the main flywheel.
[src:barring-engine/barring-engine] The drive pinion was arranged on a swinging link so that it was thrown out-of-mesh automatically, once the main engine started to rotate at full speed.
[src:barring-engine/barring-engine] As the ratio was perhaps 1000:1 and the main engine ran at 60 rpm, this would otherwise have been a disastrous overspeed.
[src:barring-engine/barring-engine] As mill engines became more powerful, from around 1870 there was a shift from single belt drives to multiple rope drives.
[src:barring-engine/barring-engine] The barring engine needed to turn these rope drives over as well (although they were disconnected from the machinery at the remote end) and a simple manual gear was no longer sufficient.
[src:barring-engine/barring-engine] Around 1881–1883 there was a shift to the use of steam-powered barring engines.
[src:barring-engine/barring-engine] Each mill engine manufacturer had their own style of barring engine.
[src:barring-engine/barring-engine] Unlike other smaller components, such as feed water pumps, they were rarely bought-in from other makers.
[src:barring-engine/barring-engine] Usually, though, a standard design was used for all sizes of engine, with additional gearing if it was required to bar a particularly large engine.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] With a global sales presence, publishing hubs, and offices in more than 40 countries, it has published over 50,000 titles by authors from over 100 countries.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] Its publications include more than 420 academic journals, monographs, reference works, school and university textbooks, and English language teaching and learning publications.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] It also publishes Bibles, runs a bookshop in Cambridge, sells through Amazon, and has a conference venues business in Cambridge at the Pitt Building and the Sir Geoffrey Cass Sports and Social Centre.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] Cambridge University Press, as part of the University of Cambridge, is a non-profit organization.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] Cambridge University Press joined The Association of American Publishers trade organization in the *Hachette v.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] Internet Archive* lawsuit which resulted in the removal of access to over 500,000 books from global readers.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] Cambridge University Press is the oldest university press in the world.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] It originated from letters patent granted to the University of Cambridge by Henry VIII in 1534.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] Cambridge was one of the two privileged presses (the other being Oxford University Press).
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] Authors published by Cambridge have included John Milton, William Harvey, Isaac Newton, Bertrand Russell, and Stephen Hawking.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] University printing began in Cambridge when the first practising University Printer, Thomas Thomas, set up a printing house in 1584.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The first publication was a book, *Two Treatises of the Lord His Holie Supper*.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In 1591, the first Cambridge Bible was printed by John Legate and in 1629, Cambridge folio edition of the King James Bible was printed by Thomas and John Buck.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In July 1697, the Duke of Somerset made a loan of £200 to the university "towards the printing house and press" and James Halman, Registrary of the university, lent £100 for the same purpose.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] A new home for the press, The Pitt Building, on Trumpington Street in the centre of Cambridge, was completed in 1833, and was designed by Edward Blore.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In the early 1800s, the press pioneers the development of stereotype printing, allowing successive printings from one setting.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The press began using steam-powered machine presses by the 1850s.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] It was in this period that the press turned down what later became the Oxford English Dictionary – a proposal for which was brought to Cambridge by James Murray before he turned to Oxford.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The press journals publishing programme began in 1893 with the *Journal of Physiology* and then the *Journal of Hygiene and Biometrika*.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] By 1910 the press had become a well-established journal publisher with a successful list which includes its first humanities title, *Modern Language Review*.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] 1956 saw the first issue of the *Journal of Fluid Mechanics*.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The press has published >170 Nobel Prize winners, the first in 1895.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In 1913, the Monotype system of hot-metal mechanised typesetting was introduced at the press.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In 1949, the press opened its first international branch in New York.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The press moved to its current site in Cambridge in 1963.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The mid-century modern building, University Printing House, was constructed in 1961–1963.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The building was designed by Beard, Bennett, Wilkins and Partners.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In 1975, the press launched its English language teaching publishing business.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In 1981, the press moved to a new site on Shaftsbury Road.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The Edinburgh Building was purpose-built with an adjoining warehouse to accommodate the press's expansion.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] It was built in 1979–80 by International Design and Construction.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The site was demolished in 2017 to make way for the construction of Cambridge Assessment's Triangle Building.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In 1989, the press acquired the long-established Bible and prayer-book publisher Eyre & Spottiswoode, which gave the press the ancient and unique title of The Queen's Printer.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In 1992, the press opened a bookshop at 1 Trinity Street, Cambridge, which was the oldest-known bookshop site in Britain, as books have been sold there since 1581.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In 2008 the shop expanded into 27 Market Hill where its specialist Education and English Language Teaching shop opened the following year.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The press bookshop sells Press books as well as Cambridge souvenirs such as mugs, diaries, bags, postcards, maps.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In 1993, the Cass Centre was opened to provide sports and social facilities for employees and their families.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In 1999, Cambridge Dictionaries Online was launched.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In 2012, the press sold its printing operation to MPG Books Group and now uses third parties around the world to provide its print publications.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In 2019, the press released a new concept in scholarly publishing through Cambridge Elements where authors whose works are either too short to be printed as a book or too long to qualify as a journal article could have these published within 12 weeks.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In 2021, Cambridge University Press merged with Cambridge Assessment.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The new organisation was called Cambridge University Press & Assessment.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In 2022, Amira Bennison was elected chair of the Cambridge University Press academic committee, replacing Kenneth Armstrong.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] Cambridge University Press has stated its support for a sustainable transition to open access.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] It offers a range of open access publishing options under the heading of Cambridge Open, allowing authors to comply with the Gold Open Access and Green Open Access requirements of major research funders.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] It published Gold Open Access journals and books and works with publishing partners such as learned societies to develop Open Access for different communities.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] It supports Green Open Access (also called Green archiving) across its journals and monographs, allowing authors to deposit content in institutional and subject-specific repositories.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] It also supports sharing on commercial sharing sites through its Cambridge Core Share service.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In recent years it has entered into several Read & Publish Open Access agreements with university libraries and consortia in several countries, including a landmark agreement with the University of California.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In its 2019 Annual Report, Cambridge University Press stated that it saw such agreements "as an important stepping stone in the transition to Open Access".
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In 2019, the press joined with the University of Cambridge's research and teaching departments to give a unified response to Plan S, which calls for all publications resulting from publicly funded research to be published in compliant open access journals or platforms from 2020.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The response emphasized Cambridge's commitment to an open access goal which works effectively for all academic disciplines, was financially sustainable for institutions and high-quality peer review, and which leads to an orderly transition.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The Press is a member of the Open Access Scholarly Publishing Association and the International Association of STM Publishers.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In 2023, more than 50 per cent of Cambridge University Press research articles were in open access mode.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] Cambridge University Press was a non-teaching department of the University of Cambridge.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The press has, since 1698, been governed by the press 'Syndics' (originally known as the 'Curators'), 18 senior members of the University of Cambridge who, along with other non-executive directors, bring a range of subject and business expertise.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The Chair of the syndicate in 2021 was Professor Stephen Toope (Vice-Chancellor of the University of Cambridge).
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The syndicate has delegated its powers to a Press & Assessment Board; and to an Academic Publishing Committee and an English Language Teaching & Education Publishing Committee.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The Press & Assessment Board is responsible for setting overarching strategic direction.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The Publishing Committees provide quality assurance and formal approval of the publishing strategy.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The operational responsibility of the press was delegated by the Syndics to the Secretary of the Syndicate and the Chief Executive.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] From 1 August 2021 onwards, Cambridge University Press became solely the academic and bible publishing division of Cambridge University Press & Assessment.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The English and education arms of the organisation merged with the equivalent departments of Cambridge Assessment to form new, merged divisions.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In 2011, Cambridge University Press adopted SAP software.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] Cambridge University Press works closely with IT services firm Tech Mahindra on SAP, and with Cognizant and Wipro on other systems.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In 2016, Cambridge Books Online and Cambridge Journals Online were replaced by Cambridge Core – a single platform to access its publishing ("the home of academic content from Cambridge University Press").
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] It provided significantly enhanced interfaces and upgraded navigation capabilities, as well as article-level and chapter-level content selection.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] A year after Cambridge Core went live, the press launched Cambridge Core Share, functionality to allow users to generate and share links with free access to selected journal articles, an early sign of the press's commitment to open research.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In 2020, Cambridge University Press partnered with online library Perlego to offer students access to digital textbooks.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The technology adapts and responds to users, "recommending course material needed to optimise learning".
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In 2021, the press began migrating its website onto Drupal.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In May 1940, CUP applied to the Inland Revenue for the exemption of its printing and publishing profits from taxation, equivalent to charitable status.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In November 1975, with CUP facing financial collapse, CUP's chief executive Geoffrey Cass wrote a 60-page "preliminary letter" to the Inland Revenue again seeking tax-exemption.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] A year later Cass's application was granted in a letter from the Inland Revenue, though the decision was not made public.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] After consulting CUP, Cambridge's 'sister' press, the giant Oxford University Press presented their own submission and received similar exemption.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In 2003 OUP's tax exemption was publicly attacked by Joel Rickett of The Bookseller in *The Guardian*.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In 2007, with the new 'public benefit' requirement of the revised Charities Act, the issue was re-examined with particular reference to the OUP.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In 2008 CUP's and OUP's privilege was attacked by rival publishers.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In 2009 *The Guardian* invited author Andrew Malcolm to write an article on the subject.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In 2007, from the National Archives at Kew, Malcolm obtained scans of CUP's unsuccessful applications for tax-exemption made in the 1940s and 1950s and their later successful applications in the 1970s.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] He then indexed and posted these on the Akmedea website.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] Late in 2020, the papers held at Kew were withdrawn from public access and ruled closed for 50 years until 1 January 2029.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] This rendered the scans on the website their only public source.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In 2021, the documents were cited in a discussion on the formation of Cambridge University Press & Assessment reported in the Cambridge University Reporter.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In 2007, controversy arose over the press's decision to destroy all remaining copies of its 2006 book *Alms for Jihad: Charity and Terrorism in the Islamic World*, by Burr and Collins, as part of the settlement of a lawsuit brought by Saudi billionaire Khalid bin Mahfouz.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] Within hours, *Alms for Jihad* became one of the 100 most sought after titles on Amazon.com and eBay in the United States.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The press sent a letter to libraries asking them to remove copies from circulation.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The press subsequently sent out copies of an "errata" sheet for the book.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In the *New York Times Book Review* (7 October 2007), United States Congressman Frank R.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] Wolf described Cambridge's settlement as "basically a book burning".
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The press pointed out that, at that time, it had already sold most of its copies of the book.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The press defended its actions, saying it had acted responsibly and that it was a global publisher with a duty to observe the laws of many different countries.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In this case, originally filed in 2008, CUP et al. accused Georgia State University of infringement of copyright.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The case closed on 29 September 2020, with GSU as the prevailing party.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] On 18 August 2017, following an "instruction" from a Chinese import agency, Cambridge University Press used the functionality that had been built into Cambridge Core to temporarily delete politically sensitive articles from *The China Quarterly* on its Chinese website.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The articles focused on topics China regards as taboo, including the 1989 Tiananmen Square massacre, Mao Zedong's Cultural Revolution, the 2014 Hong Kong protests, and ethnic tensions in Xinjiang and Tibet.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] On 21 August 2017, in the face of growing international protests, Cambridge University Press announced it would immediately repost the articles to uphold the principle of academic freedom on which the university's work was founded.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In a discussion reported in the Cambridge University Reporter, D.K.K.Chow declared, "Without academic leadership on the matter, the University's basic ethical values were cast aside by commercial considerations.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] This instigated public debate, which would have been avoided had academic leadership been more vigilant, causing unnecessary damage to the University's reputation.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In February 2021, the forthcoming *Cambridge Handbook of Privatization* was found to have included a chapter by J.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] Mark Ramseyer in which he described Koreans murdered in the Kantō Massacre of 1923 as "gangs" that "torched buildings, planted bombs, [and] poisoned water supplies".
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] Editors Avihay Dorfman and Alon Harel acknowledged the historical distortions of the chapter, but gave Ramseyer a chance to revise.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] Harel described the inclusion of the original chapter as an "innocent and very regrettable" mistake on the part of the editors.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The Press undertakes community engagement in Cambridge and around the world where there are Press employees.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] Annually, the press selects a UK Charity of the Year, which has included local charities Centre 33 (2016 and 2017), Rowan Humberstone (2018), and Castle School (2019).
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] On World Book Day 2016, the press held a digital Shakespeare publishing workshop for students and their teachers.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] Similarly, their Indian office conducted a workshop for teachers and students in 17 schools in Delhi to learn the whole process of book publishing.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The press donated more than 75,000 books in 2016.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] An apprenticeship programme for people interested in careers in publishing was established in 2016; by 2022 it had 200 active apprentices in the UK in a wide range of roles.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The Press monitors its emissions annually, has converted to energy-saving equipment, minimizes plastic use and ensures that their paper was sourced ethically.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] In 2019, the World Wildlife Fund awarded its highest score to the press of Three Trees, based on the press's timber purchasing policy, performance statement and its responsible sourcing of timber.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The press won the Independent Publishers Guild Independent Publishing Awards for sustainability in 2020 and in 2021.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] Its public commitments to sustainability include being a signatory of the UN Global Compact and to the goals of the Cambridge Zero initiative run by the University of Cambridge – to being carbon zero on all energy-related emissions by 2048.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] Cambridge University Press was a signatory of the SDG Publishers Compact, and has taken steps to support the achievement of the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) in the publishing industry.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] These include publishing a new set of open access journals known as Cambridge Prisms, relevant to the SDGs, that includes *Coastal Futures*, *Precision Medicine*, *Global Mental Health*, *Extinction*, *Plastics*, *Water* and *Drylands*.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] Cambridge also worked with the Association of Learned and Professional Society Publishers (ALPSP) to create the University Press Redux Sustainability Award in 2020.
[src:barring-engine/cambridge-university-press] The inaugural award was given to the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) for its SDG Pathfinder, an open-access digital discovery tool for finding content and data relating to the SDGs.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] A **container ship** (also called **boxship** or spelled **containership**) is a cargo ship that carries all of its load in truck-size intermodal containers, in a technique called containerization.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Container ships are a common means of commercial intermodal freight transport and now carry most seagoing non-bulk cargo.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Container ship capacity is measured in twenty-foot equivalent units (TEU).
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Typical loads are a mix of 20-foot (1-TEU) and 40-foot (2-TEU) ISO-standard containers, with the latter predominant.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Today, about 90% of non-bulk cargo worldwide is transported by container ships, the largest of which, from 2023 onward, can carry over 24,000 TEU.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] There are two main types of dry cargo: bulk cargo and break bulk cargo.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Bulk cargoes, like grain or coal, are transported unpackaged in the hull of the ship, generally in large volume.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Break-bulk cargoes, in contrast, are transported in packages, and are generally manufactured goods.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Before the advent of containerization in the 1950s, break-bulk items required manual loading, lashing, unlashing and unloading from the ship one piece at a time.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] This stevedoring process became more efficient by grouping cargo into containers, 1,000 to 3,000 cubic feet (28 to 85 m3) of cargo, or up to about 64,000 pounds (29,000 kg), is moved at once and each container is secured to the ship once in a standardized way.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Containerization has increased the efficiency of moving traditional break-bulk cargoes significantly, reducing shipping time by 84% and costs by 35%.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] In 2001, more than 90% of world trade in non-bulk goods was transported in ISO containers.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] In 2009, almost one quarter of the world's dry cargo was shipped by container, an estimated 125 million TEU or 1.19 billion tonnes worth of cargo.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The first ships designed to carry standardized load units were used in the late 18th century in England.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] In 1766 James Brindley designed the box boat "Starvationer" with 10 wooden containers, to transport coal from Worsley Delph to Manchester via the Bridgewater Canal.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Before the Second World War, the first container ships were used to carry the baggage of the luxury passenger train from London to Paris (Southern Railway's Golden Arrow / La Flèche d'Or).
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] These containers were loaded in London or Paris, and carried to ports of Dover or Calais on flat cars.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] In February 1931, the first container ship in the world was launched; the SS *Autocarrier*, owned by the Southern Railway.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] It had 21 slots for containers of Southern Railway.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The earliest container ships after the Second World War were converted oil tankers, built up from surplus T2 tankers after World War II.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] In 1951, the first purpose-built container vessels began operating in Denmark, and between Seattle and Alaska.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The first commercially successful container ship was *Ideal X*, a T2 tanker, owned by Malcom McLean, which carried 58 metal containers between Newark, New Jersey and Houston, Texas, on its first voyage.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] In 1955, McLean built his company, McLean Trucking into one of the United States' biggest freighter fleets.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] In 1955, he purchased the small Pan Atlantic Steamship Company from Waterman Steamship and adapted its ships to carry cargo in large uniform metal containers.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] On April 26, 1956, the first of these rebuilt container vessels, *Ideal X*, left the Port Newark in New Jersey and a new revolution in modern shipping resulted.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] In the 1950s, a new standardized steel Intermodal container based on specifications from the United States Department of Defense began to revolutionize freight transportation (especially for shipping companies like Seatrain Lines).
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The White Pass & Yukon Route railway acquired the world's first purpose-built container ship, the *Clifford J.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Rogers*, built in 1955, and introduced containers to its railway in 1956.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] MV *Kooringa* was the world's first fully cellular, purpose-built container ship. and was built by Australian company Associated Steamships, a partnership formed by the 1964 merger of the Adelaide Steamship Company with McIlwraith, McEacharn & Co, then commissioned in May 1964.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Container ships were designed to accommodate intermodal transport of goods, and eliminated requirements for the individual hatches, holds and other dividers of traditional cargo ships.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The hull of a typical container ship is similar to an airport hangar, or a huge warehouse, which is divided into individual holding cells, using vertical guide rails.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The ship's cells are designed to hold cargo containers, which are typically constructed of steel, though sometimes of aluminum, fiberglass or plywood, and designed for intermodal transfers between ship and train, truck or semi-trailer.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Shipping containers are categorized by type, size and function.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Today, about 90% of non-bulk cargo worldwide is transported by container by about 50,000 container ships.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Modern container ships can carry over 24,000 TEU.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The largest container ships measure about 400 metres (1,300 ft) in length, and carry loads equal to the cargo-carrying capacity of sixteen to seventeen pre-World War II freighter ships.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] There are several key points in the design of modern container ships.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The hull, similar to that of bulk carriers and general cargo ships, is built around a strong keel.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Into this frame is set one or more below-deck cargo holds, numerous tanks, and the engine room.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The holds are topped by hatch covers, onto which more containers can be stacked.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Many container ships have cargo cranes installed on them, and some have specialized systems for securing containers on board.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The hull of a modern cargo ship is a complex arrangement of steel plates and strengthening beams.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Resembling ribs, and fastened at right angles to the keel, are the ship's frames.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The ship's main deck, the metal platework that covers the top of the hull framework, is supported by beams that are attached to the tops of the frames and run the full breadth of the ship.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The beams not only support the deck, but along with the deck, frames, and transverse bulkheads, strengthen and reinforce the shell.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Another feature of recent hulls is a set of double-bottom tanks, which provide a second watertight shell that runs most of the length of a ship.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The double-bottoms generally hold liquids such as fuel oil, ballast water or fresh water.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] A ship's engine room houses its main engines and auxiliary machinery such as the fresh water and sewage systems, electrical generators, fire pumps, and air conditioners.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] In most new ships, the engine room is located in the aft portion.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Container ships are distinguished into 7 major size categories: small feeder, feeder, feedermax, Panamax, Post-Panamax, Neopanamax and ultra-large.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] As of December 2012, there were 161 container ships in the VLCS class (Very Large Container Ships, more than 10,000 TEU), and 51 ports in the world can accommodate them.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The size of a Panamax vessel is limited by the original Panama canal's lock chambers, which can accommodate ships with a beam of up to 32.31 m, a length overall of up to 294.13 m, and a draft of up to 12.04 m.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The Post-Panamax category has historically been used to describe ships with a moulded breadth over 32.31 m, however the Panama Canal expansion project has caused some changes in terminology.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The Neopanamax category is based on the maximum vessel size that is able to transit a new third set of locks, which opened in June 2016.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The third set of locks were built to accommodate a container ship with a length overall of 366 metres (1,201 ft), a maximum beam (width) of 49 metres (161 ft), and tropical fresh-water draft of 15.2 metres (50 ft).
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Such a vessel, called Neopanamax class, is wide enough to carry 19 columns of containers, can have a total capacity of approximately 12,000 TEU and is comparable in size to a capesize bulk carrier or a Suezmax tanker.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Container ships under 3,000 TEU are generally called feeder ships or feeders.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] They are small ships that typically operate between smaller container ports.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Some feeders collect their cargo from small ports, drop it off at large ports for transshipment on larger ships, and distribute containers from the large port to smaller regional ports.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] This size of vessel is the most likely to carry cargo cranes on board.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] A major characteristic of a container ship is whether it has cranes installed for handling its cargo.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Those that have cargo cranes are called *geared* and those that do not are called *ungeared* or *gearless*.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The earliest purpose-built container ships in the 1970s were all gearless.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Since then, the percentage of geared newbuilds has fluctuated widely, but has been decreasing overall, with only 7.5% of the container ship capacity in 2009 being equipped with cranes.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] While geared container ships are more flexible in that they can visit ports that are not equipped with pierside container cranes, they suffer from several drawbacks.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] To begin with, geared ships will cost more to purchase than a gearless ship.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Geared ships also incur greater recurring expenses, such as maintenance and fuel costs.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The United Nations Council on Trade and Development characterizes geared ships as a "niche market only appropriate for those ports where low cargo volumes do not justify investment in port cranes or where the public sector does not have the financial resources for such investment".
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Instead of the rotary cranes, some geared ships have gantry cranes installed.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] These cranes, specialized for container work, are able to roll forward and aft on rails.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] In addition to the additional capital expense and maintenance costs, these cranes generally load and discharge containers much more slowly than their shoreside counterparts.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The introduction and improvement of shoreside container cranes have been a key to the success of the container ship.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The first crane that was specifically designed for container work was built in California's Port of Alameda in 1959.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] By the 1980s, shoreside gantry cranes were capable of moving containers on a 3-minute-cycle, or up to 400 tons per hour.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] In March 2010, at Port Klang in Malaysia, a new world record was set when 734 container moves were made in a single hour.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The record was achieved using 9 cranes to simultaneously load and unload MV *CSCL Pusan*, a ship with a capacity of 9,600 TEU.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Vessels in the 1,500–2,499 TEU range are the most likely size class to have cranes, with more than 60% of this category being geared ships.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Slightly less than a third of the very smallest ships (from 100 to 499 TEU) are geared, and almost no ships with a capacity of over 4,000 TEU are geared.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Efficiency has always been key in the design of container ships.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] While containers may be carried on conventional break-bulk ships, cargo holds for dedicated container ships are specially constructed to speed loading and unloading, and to efficiently keep containers secure while at sea.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] A key aspect of container ship specialization is the design of the hatches, the openings from the main deck to the cargo holds.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The hatch openings stretch the entire breadth of the cargo holds, and are surrounded by a raised steel structure known as the *hatch coaming*.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] On top of the hatch coamings are the hatch covers.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Until the 1950s, hatches were typically secured with wooden boards and tarpaulins held down with battens.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Today, some hatch covers can be solid metal plates that are lifted on and off the ship by cranes, while others are articulated mechanisms that are opened and closed using powerful hydraulic rams.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Another key component of dedicated container-ship design is the use of *cell guides*.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Cell guides are strong vertical structures constructed of metal installed into a ship's cargo holds.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] These structures guide containers into well-defined rows during loading and provide some support for containers against the ship's rolling at sea.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] So fundamental to container ship design are cell guides that organizations such as the United Nations Conference on Trade and Development use their presence to distinguish dedicated container ships from general break-bulk cargo ships.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] A system of three dimensions is used in cargo plans to describe the position of a container aboard the ship.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The first coordinate is the *bay*, which starts at the front of the ship and increases aft.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Rows on the starboard side are given odd numbers and those on the port side are given even numbers.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The rows nearest the centerline are given low numbers, and the numbers increase for slots further from the centerline.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The third coordinate is the *tier*, with the first tier at the bottom of the cargo holds, the second tier on top of that, and so forth.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Container ships typically take 20 foot and 40 foot containers.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Some ships can take 45 footers above deck.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] A few ships (APL since 2007, Carrier53 since 2022 ) can carry 53 foot containers.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] 40 foot containers are the primary container size, making up about 90% of all container shipping and since container shipping moves 90% of the world's freight, over 80% of the world's freight moves via 40 foot containers.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Numerous systems are used to secure containers aboard ships, depending on factors such as the type of ship, the type of container, and the location of the container.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Storage inside the holds of fully cellular (FC) ships is simplest, typically using simple metal forms called container guides, locating cones, and anti-rack spacers to lock the containers together.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Above-decks, without the extra support of the cell guides, more complicated equipment is used.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Three types of systems are currently in wide use: lashing systems, locking systems, and buttress systems.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Lashing systems secure containers to the ship using devices made from wire rope, rigid rods, or chains and devices to tension the lashings, such as turnbuckles.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The effectiveness of lashings is increased by securing containers to each other, either by simple metal forms (such as stacking cones) or more complicated devices such as twist-lock stackers.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] A typical twist-lock is inserted into the casting hole of one container and rotated to hold it in place, then another container is lowered on top of it.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The two containers are locked together by twisting the device's handle.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] A typical twist-lock is constructed of forged steel and ductile iron and has a shear strength of 48 tonnes.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The buttress system, used on some large container ships, uses a system of large towers attached to the ship at both ends of each cargo hold.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] As the ship is loaded, a rigid, removable stacking frame is added, structurally securing each tier of containers together.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Container ships have typically had a single bridge and accommodation unit towards the rear, but to reconcile demand for larger container capacity with SOLAS visibility requirements, several new designs have been developed.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] As of 2015, some large container ships are being developed with the bridge further forward, separate from the exhaust stack.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Some smaller container ships working in European ports and rivers have liftable wheelhouses, which can be lowered to pass under low bridges.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] As of 2010, container ships made up 13.3% of the world's fleet in terms of deadweight tonnage.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The world's total of container ship deadweight tonnage has increased from 11 million DWT in 1980 to 169.0 million DWT in 2010.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The combined deadweight tonnage of container ships and general cargo ships, which also often carry containers, represents 21.8% of the world's fleet.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] As of 2009, the average age of container ships worldwide was 10.6 years, making them the youngest general vessel type, followed by bulk carriers at 16.6 years, oil tankers at 17 years, general cargo ships at 24.6 years, and others at 25.3 years.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Most of the world's carrying capacity in fully cellular container ships is in the liner service, where ships trade on scheduled routes.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] As of January 2010, the top 20 liner companies controlled 67.5% of the world's fully cellular container capacity, with 2,673 vessels of an average capacity of 3,774 TEU.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The remaining 6,862 fully cellular ships have an average capacity of 709 TEU each.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The vast majority of the capacity of fully cellular container ships used in the liner trade is owned by German shipowners, with approximately 75% owned by Hamburg brokers.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] It is a common practice for the large container lines to supplement their own ships with chartered-in ships, for example in 2009, 48.9% of the tonnage of the top 20 liner companies was chartered-in in this manner.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] International law requires that every merchant ship be registered in a country, called its flag state.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] A ship's flag state exercises regulatory control over the vessel and is required to inspect it regularly, certify the ship's equipment and crew, and issue safety and pollution prevention documents.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] As of 2006, the United States Bureau of Transportation Statistics count 2,837 container ships of 10,000 long tons deadweight (DWT) or greater worldwide.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Panama was the world's largest flag state for container ships, with 541 of the vessels in its registry.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Seven other flag states had more than 100 registered container ships: Liberia (415), Germany (248), Singapore (177), Cyprus (139), the Marshall Islands (118) and the United Kingdom (104).
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The Panamanian, Liberian, and Marshallese flags are open registries and considered by the International Transport Workers' Federation to be flags of convenience.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] By way of comparison, traditional maritime nations such as the United States and Japan only had 75 and 11 registered container ships, respectively.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] In recent years, oversupply of container ship capacity has caused prices for new and used ships to fall.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] From 2008 to 2009, new container ship prices dropped by 19–33%, while prices for 10-year-old container ships dropped by 47–69%.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] In March 2010, the average price for a geared 500-TEU container ship was $10 million, while gearless ships of 6,500 and 12,000 TEU averaged prices of $74 million and $105 million respectively.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] At the same time, secondhand prices for 10-year-old geared container ships of 500-, 2,500-, and 3,500-TEU capacity averaged prices of $4 million, $15 million, and $18 million respectively.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] In 2009, 11,669,000 gross tons of newly built container ships were delivered.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Over 85% of this new capacity was built in the Republic of Korea, China, and Japan, with Korea accounting for over 57% of the world's total alone.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] New container ships accounted for 15% of the total new tonnage that year, behind bulk carriers at 28.9% and oil tankers at 22.6%.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Most ships are removed from the fleet through a process known as scrapping.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Scrapping is rare for ships under 18 years old and common for those over 40 years in age.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Ship-owners and buyers negotiate scrap prices based on factors such as the ship's empty weight (called light ton displacement or LTD) and prices in the scrap metal market.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Scrapping rates are volatile, the price per light ton displacement has swung from a high of $650 per LTD in mid-2008 to $200 per LTD in early 2009, before building to $400 per LTD in March 2010.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] As of 2009, over 96% of the world's scrapping activity takes place in China, India, Bangladesh, and Pakistan.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The global economic downturn of 2008–2009 resulted in more ships than usual being sold for scrap.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] In 2009, 364,300 TEU worth of container ship capacity was scrapped, up from 99,900 TEU in 2008.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Container ships accounted for 22.6% of the total gross tonnage of ships scrapped that year.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Despite the surge, the capacity removed from the fleet only accounted for 3% of the world's container ship capacity.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The average age of container ships scrapped in 2009 was 27.0 years.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Economies of scale have dictated an upward trend in the size of container ships in order to reduce expenses.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] However, there are certain limitations to the size of container ships.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Primarily, these are the availability of sufficiently large main engines and the availability of a sufficient number of ports and terminals prepared and equipped to handle ultra-large container ships.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Furthermore, the permissible maximum ship dimensions in some of the world's main waterways could present an upper limit in terms of vessel growth.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] This primarily concerns the Suez Canal and the Singapore Strait.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] In 2008 the South Korean shipbuilder STX announced plans to construct a container ship capable of carrying 22,000 TEU, and with a proposed length of 450 m (1,480 ft) and a beam of 60 m (200 ft).
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] If constructed, the container ship would become the largest seagoing vessel in the world.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Since even very large container ships are vessels with relatively low draft compared to large tankers and bulk carriers, there is still considerable room for vessel growth.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Compared to today's largest container ships, Maersk Line's 15,200 TEU *Emma Mærsk*-type series, a 20,000 TEU container ship would only be moderately larger in terms of exterior dimensions.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] It would have an estimated deadweight of circa 220,000 tons.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] In 2011, Maersk announced plans to build a new "Triple E" family of container ships with a capacity of 18,000 TEU, with an emphasis on lower fuel consumption.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] In the present market situation, main engines will not be as much of a limiting factor for vessel growth either.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The steadily rising expense of fuel oil in the early 2010s had prompted most container lines to adapt a slower, more economical voyage speed of about 21 knots, compared to earlier top speeds of 25 or more knots.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Subsequently, newly built container ships can be fitted with a smaller main engine.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Engine types fitted to today's ships of 14,000 TEU are thus sufficiently large to propel future vessels of 20,000 TEU or more.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Maersk Line, the world's largest container shipping line, nevertheless opted for twin engines (two smaller engines working two separate propellers), when ordering a series of ten 18,000 TEU vessels from Daewoo Shipbuilding in February 2011.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The ships were delivered between 2013 and 2014.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] In 2016, some experts believed that the current largest container ships are at the optimum size, and could not economically be larger, as port facilities would be too expensive, port handling too time-consuming, the number of suitable ports too low, and insurance cost too high.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] In March 2017 the first ship with an official capacity over 20,000 TEUs was christened at Samsung Heavy Industries.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] *MOL Triumph* has a capacity of 20,150 TEUs.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Samsung Heavy Industries was expected to deliver several ships of over 20,000 TEUs in 2017, and has orders for at least ten vessels in that size range for OOCL and MOL.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The world's largest container ship, *MSC Irina*, was delivered March 9, 2023 by builder Yangzi Xinfu Shipbuilding to the Mediterranean Shipping Company (MSC), with a capacity of 24,346 TEUs.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Measuring 399.99 metres in length and 61.3 metres in beam, the ship is one of four ordered from the builder in 2020, and exceeded MSC's 24,116 TEU *MSC Tessa*, which had been delivered that same day by the China State Shipbuilding Corporation (CSSC).
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] In April, *MSC Irina* sister ship *MSC Loreto*, with an equal capacity of 24,346 TEU was received by MSC.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] On June 2, 2023 Ocean Network Express took delivery of the *ONE Innovation* with a capacity of 24,136 TEUs.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] *ONE Innovation* is one of six new Megamax vessels ordered by Ocean Network Express in December 2020 to be built by a consortium of Imabari Shipbuilding and Japan Marine United.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The act of hiring a ship to carry cargo is called chartering.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Outside special bulk cargo markets, ships are hired by three types of charter agreements: the voyage charter, the time charter, and the bareboat charter.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] In a voyage charter, the charterer rents the vessel from the loading port to the discharge port.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] In a time charter, the vessel is hired for a set period of time, to perform voyages as the charterer directs.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] In a bareboat charter, the charterer acts as the ship's operator and manager, taking on responsibilities such as providing the crew and maintaining the vessel.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The completed chartering contract is known as a charter party.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The United Nations Conference on Trade and Development [UNCTAD], tracks in its 2010 *Review of Maritime Trade* two aspects of container shipping prices: The first one is a chartering price, specifically the price to time-charter a 1 TEU slot for 14 tonnes of cargo on a container ship.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The other is the freight rate; or comprehensive daily cost to deliver one-TEU worth of cargo on a given route.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] As a result of the late-2000s recession, both indicators showed sharp drops during 2008–2009, and have shown signs of stabilization since 2010.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] UNCTAD uses the Hamburg Shipbrokers' Association (formally the *Vereinigung Hamburger Schiffsmakler und Schiffsagenten e.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] V.* or VHSS for short) as its main industry source for container ship freight prices.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The VHSS maintains a few indices of container ship charter prices.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The oldest, which dates back to 1998, is called the *Hamburg Index*.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] This index considers time-charters on fully cellular container ships controlled by Hamburg brokers.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] It is limited to charters of 3 months or more, and presented as the average daily cost in U.S. dollars for a one-TEU slot with a weight of 14 tonnes.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The Hamburg Index data is divided into ten categories based primarily on vessel carrying capacity.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Two additional categories exist for small vessels of under 500 TEU that carry their own cargo cranes.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] In 2007, VHSS started another index, the *New ConTex* which tracks similar data obtained from an international group of shipbrokers.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The Hamburg Index shows some clear trends in recent chartering markets.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] First, rates were generally increasing from 2000 to 2005.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] From 2005 to 2008, rates slowly decreased, and in mid-2008 began a "dramatic decline" of approximately 75%, which lasted until rates stabilized in April 2009.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Rates have ranged from $2.70 to $35.40 in this period, with prices generally lower on larger ships.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The most resilient sized vessel in this time period were those from 200 to 300 TEU, a fact that the United Nations Council on Trade and Development attributes to lack of competition in this sector.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Overall, in 2010, these rates rebounded somewhat, but remained at approximately half of their 2008 values.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] As of 2011, the index shows signs of recovery for container shipping, and combined with increases in global capacity, indicates a positive outlook for the sector in the near future.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] UNCTAD also tracks container freight rates.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Freight rates are expressed as the total price in U.S. dollars for a shipper to transport one TEU worth of cargo along a given route.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Data is given for the three main container liner routes: U.S.-Asia, U.S.-Europe, and Europe-Asia.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Prices are typically different between the two legs of a voyage, for example the Asia-U.S. rates have been significantly higher than the return U.S.-Asia rates in recent years.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Generally, from the fourth quarter of 2008 through the third quarter of 2009, both the volume of container cargo and freight rates have dropped sharply.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] In 2009, the freight rates on the U.S.–Europe route were sturdiest, while the Asia-U.S. route fell the most.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Liner companies responded to their overcapacity in several ways.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] For example, in early 2009, some container lines dropped their freight rates to zero on the Asia-Europe route, charging shippers only a surcharge to cover operating costs.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] They decreased their overcapacity by lowering the ships' speed (a strategy called "slow steaming") and by laying up ships.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Slow steaming increased the length of the Europe-Asia routes to a record high of over 40 days.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Another strategy used by some companies was to manipulate the market by publishing notices of rate increases in the press, and when "a notice had been issued by one carrier, other carriers followed suit".
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The Trans-Siberian Railroad (TSR) has recently become a more viable alternative to container ships on the Asia-Europe route.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] This railroad can typically deliver containers in 1/3 to 1/2 of the time of a sea voyage, and in late 2009 announced a 20% reduction in its container shipping rates.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] With its 2009 rate schedule, the TSR will transport a forty-foot container to Poland from Yokohama for $2,820, or from Pusan for $2,154.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] In an effort to control costs and maximize capacity utilization on ever-larger ships, vessel sharing agreements, co-operative agreements, and slot-exchanges have become a growing feature of the maritime container shipping industry.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] As of March 2015, 16 of the world's largest container shipping lines had consolidated their routes and services accounting for 95 percent of container cargo volumes moving in the dominant east–west trade routes.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Carriers remain operationally independent, as they are forbidden by antitrust regulators in multiple jurisdictions from colluding on freight rates or capacity.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Similarities can be drawn with airline alliances.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] The shipping companies announced a series of commitments aiming to address the commission's concerns, which for its part the Commission accepted as "legally binding" for the period from 2016 to 2019.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] General Rate Increases continue to be published in the industry either annually or sixth-monthly.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Container traffic through a port is often tracked in terms of twenty foot equivalent units or TEU of throughput.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] As of 2019, the Port of Shanghai was the world's busiest container port, with 43,303,000 TEU handled.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] That year, seven of the busiest ten container ports were in the People's Republic of China, with Shanghai in 1st place, Ningbo 3rd, Shenzhen 4th, Guangzhou 5th, Qingdao 7th, Hong Kong 8th and Tianjin 9th.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Rounding out the top ten ports were Singapore at 2nd, Busan in South Korea at 6th and Rotterdam in the Netherlands in the 10th position.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] In total, the busiest twenty container ports handled 220,905,805 TEU in 2009, almost half of the world's total estimated container traffic that year of 465,597,537 TEU.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] It has been estimated that container ships lose between 2,000 and 10,000 containers at sea each year, costing $370 million.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] However, in the 3-year period from 2017 to 2019, that number was nearly halved, down to an average of 779 containers lost annually.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Most go overboard on the open sea during storms but there are some examples of whole ships being lost with their cargo.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] One major shipping accident occurred in 2013 when the MOL Comfort sank with 4,293 containers on board in the Indian Ocean.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] When containers are dropped, they immediately become an environmental threat – termed "marine debris".
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Once in the ocean, they fill with water and sink if the contents cannot hold air.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] Rough waters smash the container, sinking it quickly.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] As container ships get larger and stacking becomes higher, the threat of containers toppling into the sea during a storm increases.
[src:barring-engine/container-ships] This results from a phenomenon called "parametric rolling," by which a ship can roll 30-40 degrees during rough seas creating a powerful torque on a 10-high stack of containers which can easily snap lashings and locks of the stack, resulting in losses into the sea.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] It is adjacent to Erith Marshes, a grazing marsh, the northern part of which is designated as Crossness Nature Reserve.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] This provides a valuable habitat for creatures ranging from moths to small amphibians and water voles.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] At Crossness, the incoming liquid was raised some 30 to 40 feet (9–12 m) by the application of four large steam driven pumps.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] The engines were of enormous size and power.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] They were built by James Watt & Co. to Joseph Bazalgette's designs and specification, and were named "Victoria", "Prince Consort", "Albert Edward" and "Alexandra".
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] At 11 revolutions per minute, 6 tons (approximately 1,500 imp gal or 6,800 L) of sewage per stroke per engine were pumped up into a 27-million-imperial-gallon (120,000 m3) reservoir, and was released into the Thames during the ebbing tide.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] The steam required to power these engines was raised by 12 Cornish boilers with single "straight-through" flues situated in the Boiler House to the south of the Engine House, and which consumed 5,000 tons of Welsh coal annually.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] The Crossness Works merely disposed of raw sewage into the river seawards, and in 1882, a Royal Commission recommended that the solid matter in the sewage should be separated out, and that only the liquid portion remaining should be allowed, as a temporary measure, to pass into the river.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] In 1891, sedimentation tanks were added to the works, and the sludge was carried by steam boats and dumped further out into the estuary, at sea.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] By 1897, additional pumping capacity was needed, and four extra pumps operated by triple-expansion steam engines were installed in an extension, designed to fit in with Bazalgette's main engine house, to the north of the older building.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] Later, in 1899, a further increase in London's population necessitated an increase in the efficiency of the original Watt engines, and considerable alteration to their design was carried out by Goodfellow & Co of Hyde, Manchester, for London County Council.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] They were converted from simple to compound engines, with the original single cylinders augmented by high and intermediate pressure cylinders.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] The additional steam required was provided by replacing the earlier Cornish boilers by more efficient Lancashire boilers with double flues and in 1901, the improved engines were fully working.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] When the pumping station was decommissioned in the 1950s, it was not considered economic to dismantle the engines, as the cost of doing so far exceeded any scrap value.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] The more valuable metal items (made from brass), such as the engine oilers, much pipework, and even the handrails from the stairs, were removed.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] The remaining building and engines were left to decay and over the decades were subject to much vandalism.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] The pumping station became a Grade I listed building in 1970 and remains on the Heritage at Risk Register.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] The Crossness Engines Trust, a registered charity, was formed in 1987 to oversee the restoration project.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] The four pumping engines are thought to be the largest remaining rotative beam engines in the world, with 52-ton flywheels and 47-ton beams.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] As Prince Consort was the last steam engine decommissioned, in 1953, it is this engine on which the restoration activity has been concentrated.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] After fifteen years of effort, by 2003 the engine was in working order again and is run on the open days organised by the Trust.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] Work has since begun on the restoration of Victoria.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] When the buildings were abandoned, the pumps and culverts and all the subterranean areas below the Beam Engine House were filled with sand to reduce the risks from methane.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] This has meant that some 100 tons of this sand has had to be excavated from around and underneath the pumps before there was any hope of moving the beam and flywheel.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] There was also a large ingress of rain water, resulting in serious rusting of the engine parts.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] The original boilers did not survive, and Prince Consort is now steamed by a small "off the shelf" boiler.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] While it only has a fraction of the steam capacity of the originals, this is not a problem as the engine no longer operates under load.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] Financial and other support was also provided by Thames Water, Tilfen Land, the London Borough of Bexley and the City Bridge Trust.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] A further £1.5 million in funding from the Heritage Lottery Fund was secured in April 2015, the 150th anniversary of Crossness's official opening.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] This was to help fund a museum exhibition focused on the "Great Stink" of 1858 and the role of Crossness in improving London's sewerage system.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] Crossness Pumping Station was opened to the public in 2016.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] The 2003 BBC Series *Seven Wonders of the Industrial World: The Sewer King* episode featured a segment filmed in the pumping station.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] The pumping station has been used as a filming location for the 2009 film *Sherlock Holmes* and for the 2011 BBC production of Michel Faber's *The Crimson Petal and the White*.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] The building was also used as the setting for the final mission of the video game *The Getaway: Black Monday*.
[src:barring-engine/crossness-pumping-station] The pumping station is used as the interior of Gustafson's factory in the 2020 film *Jingle Jangle: A Christmas Journey*, and was the location for the 2021 revival of *GamesMaster*.
[src:barring-engine/dead-centre-engineering] In a reciprocating engine, the **dead centre** is the position of a piston in which it is either furthest from, or nearest to, the crankshaft.
[src:barring-engine/dead-centre-engineering] The former is known as **top dead centre** (**TDC**) while the latter is known as **bottom dead centre** (**BDC**).
[src:barring-engine/dead-centre-engineering] More generally, the dead centre is any position of a crank where the applied force is straight along its axis, meaning no turning force can be applied.
[src:barring-engine/dead-centre-engineering] Many sorts of machines are crank driven, including unicycles, bicycles, tricycles, various types of machine presses, gasoline engines, diesel engines, steam locomotives, and other steam engines.
[src:barring-engine/dead-centre-engineering] Crank-driven machines rely on the energy stored in a flywheel to overcome the dead centre, or are designed, in the case of multi-cylinder engines, so that dead centres can never exist on all cranks at the same time.
[src:barring-engine/dead-centre-engineering] A steam locomotive is an example of the latter, the connecting rods being arranged such that the dead centre for each cylinder occurs out of phase with the other one (or more) cylinders.
[src:barring-engine/dead-centre-engineering] Bicycle cranks have dead centres at approximately 12 o'clock and 6 o'clock where simple pushing down of the pedal will not turn the chainwheel, but the rider's leg can apply tangential force at the pedal to overcome it.
[src:barring-engine/dead-centre-engineering] Fixed-gear bicycles (without a freehub) use the momentum of the bicycle and rider to keep the chainwheel turning even if the rider makes no attempt to pedal in a circular motion.
[src:barring-engine/dead-centre-engineering] In a reciprocating engine, top dead centre of piston #1 is the point from which ignition system measurements are made and the firing order is determined.
[src:barring-engine/dead-centre-engineering] For example, ignition timing is normally specified as degrees of crankshaft rotation **before top dead centre** (**BTDC**).
[src:barring-engine/dead-centre-engineering] A very few small and fast-burning engines require a spark just **after top dead centre** (**ATDC**), such as the Nissan MA engine with hemispherical combustions, or hydrogen engines.
[src:barring-engine/dead-centre-engineering] Top dead centre for cylinder one is often marked on the crankshaft pulley, the flywheel or harmonic balancer or both, with adjacent timing marks showing the recommended ignition timing settings as decided during engine development.
[src:barring-engine/dead-centre-engineering] The timing marks can be used to set the ignition timing either statically by hand or dynamically using a timing light, by rotating the distributor in its seat.
[src:barring-engine/dead-centre-engineering] In a multi-cylinder engine, pistons may reach top dead centre simultaneously or at different times depending on the engine configuration.
[src:barring-engine/dead-centre-engineering] The concept of top dead centre is also extended to pistonless rotary engines, and means the point in the cycle in which the volume of a combustion chamber is smallest.
[src:barring-engine/dead-centre-engineering] This typically occurs several times per rotor revolution.
[src:barring-engine/dead-centre-engineering] In the Wankel engine for example, it occurs three times for every one revolution of the rotor (although only once per revolution of the engine output shaft, since the output rotates at three times the speed of the rotor).
[src:barring-engine/dead-centre-engineering] Finding the volume of the cylinder using TDC and BDC and multiplying it by the number of cylinders will give the engine displacement.
[src:barring-engine/dead-centre-engineering] As steam engines are commonly horizontal, the relevant terms are front dead centre and back dead centre rather than "top" and "bottom".
[src:barring-engine/dead-centre-engineering] If a single-cylinder steam engine stops in either of the dead centre positions, it must be moved off the dead centre before it will restart.
[src:barring-engine/dead-centre-engineering] In small engines, this is done by turning the flywheel by hand.
[src:barring-engine/dead-centre-engineering] In large engines, the flywheel is moved with a lever or "turning bar".
[src:barring-engine/dead-centre-engineering] Both operations must be done with care to avoid the operator becoming entangled in the machinery.
[src:barring-engine/dead-centre-engineering] Even larger engines might require the use of a barring engine.
[src:barring-engine/dead-centre-engineering] Steam locomotives normally have at least two double acting cylinders, which enables the cranks to be set so that at least one piston will always be off the dead centre and no starting assistance is required.
[src:barring-engine/dead-centre-engineering] In the common case of a two piston locomotive, the cranks are set at right angles, so that whenever one piston is at dead centre the other is in mid-stroke, and giving four equally spaced power strokes per revolution.
[src:barring-engine/dead-centre-engineering] This term is also used in the realm of production equipment.
[src:barring-engine/dead-centre-engineering] A mechanical punch press employs a crankshaft similar to that found in an engine.
[src:barring-engine/dead-centre-engineering] In the punch press, the crankshaft drives a ram that when it is furthest away from the platen of the press is deemed to be in the position of top dead centre.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] A **starter** (also **self-starter**, **cranking motor**, or **starter motor**) is an apparatus installed in motor vehicles to rotate the crankshaft of an internal combustion engine so as to initiate the engine's combustion cycle.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Starters can be electric, pneumatic, or hydraulic.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The starter can also be another internal combustion engine in the case, for instance, of very large engines, or diesel engines in agricultural or excavation applications.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Internal combustion engines are feedback systems, which, once started, rely on the inertia from each cycle to initiate the next cycle.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] In a four-stroke engine, the third stroke releases energy from the fuel, powering the fourth (exhaust) stroke and also the first two (intake, compression) strokes of the next cycle, as well as powering the engine's external load.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] To start the first cycle at the beginning of any particular session, the first two strokes must be powered in some other way than from the engine itself.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The starter motor is used for this purpose and it is not required once the engine starts running and its feedback loop becomes self-sustaining.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The hand-crank method was commonly used to start engines, but it was inconvenient, difficult, and dangerous.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The behavior of an engine during starting is not always predictable.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The engine can kick back, causing sudden reverse rotation.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Many manual starters included a one-directional slip or release provision so that once engine rotation began, the starter would disengage from the engine.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] In the event of a kickback, the reverse rotation of the engine could suddenly engage the starter, causing the crank to unexpectedly and violently jerk, possibly injuring the operator.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] For cord-wound starters, a kickback could pull the operator towards the engine or machine, or swing the starter cord and handle at high speed around the starter pulley.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Even though cranks had an overrun mechanism, when the engine started, the crank could begin to spin along with the crankshaft and potentially strike the person cranking the engine.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Additionally, care had to be taken to retard the spark in order to prevent backfiring; with an advanced spark setting, the engine could *kick back* (run in reverse), pulling the crank with it, because the overrun safety mechanism works in one direction only.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Although users were advised to cup their fingers and thumb under the crank and pull up, it felt natural for operators to grasp the handle with the fingers on one side, the thumb on the other.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Even a simple backfire could result in a broken thumb; it was possible to end up with a broken wrist, a dislocated shoulder or worse.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Moreover, increasingly larger engines with higher compression ratios made hand cranking a more physically demanding endeavour.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The first electric starter was installed on an Arnold, an adaptation of the Benz Velo, built in 1896 in East Peckham, England, by electrical engineer H.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Coleman invented and patented the first electric starter in America U.S. patent 0,745,157.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Leland, of Dayton Engineering Laboratories Company (DELCO), invented and filed U.S. patent 1,150,523 for an electric starter in America.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] One aspect of the invention lay in the realization that a relatively small motor, driven with higher voltage and current than would be feasible for continuous operation, could deliver enough power to crank the engine for starting.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] At the voltage and current levels required, such a motor would burn out in a few minutes of continuous operation, but not during the few seconds needed to start the engine.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The starters were first installed on the Cadillac Model Thirty in 1912, with the same system being adopted by Lanchester later that year.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] These starters also worked as generators once the engine was running, a concept that is now being revived in hybrid vehicles.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The Star and Adler cars had spring motors (sometimes referred to as clockwork motors), which used the energy stored in a spring driving through a reduction gear.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] If the car failed to start, the starter handle could be used to wind up the spring for a further attempt.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] One of the innovations on the first Dodge car, the Model 30-35 at its introduction in 1914 was an electric starter and electric lighting with a 12-volt system (against the six volts that was usual at the time) as a standard fitment on what was a relatively low-priced car.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The Dodge used a combined starter-generator unit, with a direct current dynamo permanently coupled by gears to the engine's crankshaft.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] A system of electrical relays allowed this to be driven as a motor to rotate the engine for starting, and once the starter button was released the controlling switchgear returned the unit to operation as a generator.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Because the starter-generator was directly coupled to the engine it did not need a method of engaging and disengaging the motor drive.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] It thus suffered negligible mechanical wear and was virtually silent in operation.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The starter-generator remained a feature of Dodge cars until 1929.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The disadvantage of the design was that, as a dual-purpose device, the unit was limited in both its power as a motor and its output as a generator, which became a problem as engine size and electrical demands on cars increased.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Controlling the switch between motor and generator modes required dedicated and relatively complex switchgear which was more prone to failure than the heavy-duty contacts of a dedicated starter motor.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] These were marketed under the 'Dynastart' name.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Since motorcycles usually had small engines and limited electrical equipment, as well as restricted space and weight, the Dynastart was a useful feature.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The windings for the starter-generator were usually incorporated into the engine's flywheel, thus not requiring a separate unit at all.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The Ford Model T relied on hand cranks until 1919; during the 1920s, electric starters became near-universal on most new cars, making it easier for women and elderly people to drive.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] It was still common for cars to be supplied with starter handles into the 1960s, and this continued much later for some makes (e.g.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Citroën 2CV until end of production in 1990).
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] In many cases, cranks were used for setting timing rather than starting the engine as growing displacements and compression ratios made this impractical.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Communist bloc cars such as Ladas often still supported crank-starting as late as the 1980s.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Before Chrysler's 1949 innovation of the key-operated combination ignition-starter switch, the starter was often operated by the driver pressing a button mounted on the floor or dashboard.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Some vehicles had a pedal in the floor that manually engaged the starter drive pinion with the flywheel ring gear, then completed the electrical circuit to the starter motor once the pedal reached the end of its travel.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Ferguson tractors from the 1940s, including the Ferguson TE20, had an extra position on the gear lever that engaged the starter switch, ensuring safety by preventing the tractors from being started in gear.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The electric **starter motor** or **cranking motor** is the most common type used on gasoline engines and small diesel engines.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The modern starter motor is either a permanent-magnet or a series-parallel wound direct current electric motor with a starter solenoid (similar to a relay) mounted on it.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] When DC power from the starting battery is applied to the solenoid, usually through a key-operated switch (the "ignition switch"), the solenoid engages a lever that pushes out the drive pinion on the starter driveshaft and meshes the pinion with the starter ring gear on the flywheel of the engine.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The solenoid also closes high-current contacts for the starter motor, which begins to turn.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Once the engine starts, the key-operated switch is opened, a spring in the solenoid assembly pulls the pinion gear away from the ring gear, and the starter motor stops.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The starter's pinion is clutched to its drive shaft through an overrunning sprag clutch which permits the pinion to transmit drive in only one direction.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] This prevents the engine driving the starter, for such backdrive would cause the starter to spin so fast as to fly apart.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The sprag clutch arrangement would preclude the use of the starter as a generator if employed in the hybrid scheme mentioned above, unless modifications were made.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The standard starter motor is typically designed for intermittent use, which would preclude its use as a generator.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The starter's electrical components are designed only to operate for typically under 30 seconds before overheating (by too-slow dissipation of heat from ohmic losses), to save weight and cost.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Most automobile owner manuals instruct the operator to pause for at least ten seconds after each ten or fifteen seconds of cranking the engine, when trying to start an engine that does not start immediately.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] This overrunning-clutch pinion arrangement was phased into use beginning in the early 1960s; before that time, a Bendix drive was used.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The Bendix system places the starter drive pinion on a helically cut drive shaft.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] When the starter motor begins turning, the inertia of the drive pinion assembly causes it to ride forward on the helix and thus engage with the ring gear.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] When the engine starts, backdrive from the ring gear causes the drive pinion to exceed the rotative speed of the starter, at which point the drive pinion is forced back down the helical shaft and thus out of mesh with the ring gear.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] This has the disadvantage that the gears will disengage if the engine fires briefly but does not continue to run.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] An intermediate development between the Bendix drive developed in the 1930s and the overrunning-clutch designs introduced in the 1960s was the Bendix Folo-Thru drive.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The standard Bendix drive would disengage from the ring gear as soon as the engine fired, even if it did not continue to run.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The Folo-Thru drive contains a latching mechanism and a set of flyweights in the body of the drive unit.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] When the starter motor begins turning and the drive unit is forced forward on the helical shaft by inertia, it is latched into the engaged position.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Only once the drive unit is spun at a speed higher than that attained by the starter motor itself (i.e., it is backdriven by the running engine) will the flyweights pull radially outward, releasing the latch and permitting the overdriven drive unit to be spun out of engagement.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] In this manner, unwanted starter disengagement is avoided before a successful engine start.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] In 1962, Chrysler introduced a starter incorporating a geartrain between the motor and the drive shaft.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The motor shaft included integrally cut gear teeth forming a pinion that meshes with a larger adjacent driven gear to provide a gear reduction ratio of 3.75:1.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] This permitted the use of a higher-speed, lower-current, lighter and more compact motor assembly while increasing cranking torque.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Variants of this starter design were used on most rear- and four-wheel-drive vehicles produced by Chrysler Corporation from 1962 through 1987.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] It makes a unique, distinct sound when cranking the engine, which led to it being nicknamed the "Highland Park Hummingbird"—a reference to Chrysler's headquarters in Highland Park, Michigan.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The Chrysler gear-reduction starter formed the conceptual basis for the gear-reduction starters that now predominate in vehicles on the road.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Many Japanese automakers phased in gear reduction starters in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Light aircraft engines also made extensive use of this kind of starter, because its light weight offered an advantage.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Those starters not employing offset gear trains like the Chrysler unit generally employ planetary epicyclic gear trains instead.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Direct-drive starters are almost entirely obsolete owing to their larger size, heavier weight and higher current requirements.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Ford issued a nonstandard starter, a direct-drive "movable pole shoe" design that provided cost reduction rather than electrical or mechanical benefits.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] This type of starter eliminated the solenoid, replacing it with a movable pole shoe and a separate starter relay.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] This starter operates as follows: The driver turns the key, activating the starter switch.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] A small electric current flows through the solenoid actuated starter relay, closing the contacts and sending large battery current to the starter motor.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] One of the pole shoes, hinged at the front, linked to the starter drive, and spring-loaded away from its normal operating position, is swung into position by the magnetic field created by electricity flowing through its field coil.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] This moves the starter drive forward to engage the flywheel ring gear, and simultaneously closes a pair of contacts supplying current to the rest of the starter motor winding.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Once the engine starts and the driver releases the starter switch, a spring retracts the pole shoe, which pulls the starter drive out of engagement with the ring gear.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] This starter was used on Ford vehicles from 1973 through 1990, when a gear-reduction unit conceptually similar to the Chrysler unit replaced it.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] A variant on the electric starter motor is the inertia starter (not to be confused with the Bendix-type starter described above).
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Here the starter motor does not turn the engine directly.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Instead, when energized, the motor turns a heavy flywheel built into its casing (not the main flywheel of the engine).
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Once the flywheel/motor unit has reached a constant speed the current to the motor is turned off and the drive between the motor and flywheel is disengaged by a freewheel mechanism.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The spinning flywheel is then connected to the main engine and its inertia turns it over to start it.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] These stages are commonly automated by solenoid switches, with the machine operator using a two-position control switch, which is held in one position to spin the motor and then moved to the other to cut the current to the motor and engage the flywheel to the engine.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The advantage of the inertia starter is that, because the motor is not driving the engine directly, it can be of much lower power than the standard starter for an engine of the same size.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] This allows for a motor of much lower weight and smaller size, as well as lighter cables and smaller batteries to power the motor.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] This made the inertia starter a common choice for aircraft with large radial piston engines.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The disadvantage is the increased time required to start the engine - spinning up the flywheel to the required speed can take between 10 and 20 seconds.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] If the engine does not start by the time the flywheel has lost its inertia then the process must be repeated for the next attempt.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Some gas turbine engines and diesel engines, particularly on trucks, use a pneumatic self-starter.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] In ground vehicles the system consists of a geared turbine, an air compressor and a pressure tank.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Compressed air released from the tank is used to spin the turbine, and through a set of reduction gears, engages the ring gear on the flywheel, much like an electric starter.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The engine, once running, drives the compressor to recharge the tank.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Aircraft with large gas turbine engines are typically started using a large volume of low-pressure compressed air, supplied from a very small engine referred to as an auxiliary power unit, located elsewhere in the aircraft.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Alternatively, aircraft gas turbine engines can be rapidly started using a mobile ground-based pneumatic starting engine, referred to as a *start cart* or *air start cart*.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] On larger diesel generators found in large shore installations and especially on ships, a pneumatic starting gear is used.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The air motor is normally powered by compressed air at pressures of 10–30 bar.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The air motor is made up of a center drum about the size of a soup can with four or more slots cut into it to allow for the vanes to be placed radially on the drum to form chambers around the drum.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The drum is offset inside a round casing so that the inlet air for starting is admitted at the area where the drum and vanes form a small chamber compared to the others.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The compressed air can only expand by rotating the drum, which allows the small chamber to become larger and puts another one of the cambers in the air inlet.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The air motor spins much too fast to be used directly on the flywheel of the engine; instead a large gearing reduction, such as a planetary gear, is used to lower the output speed.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] A Bendix gear is used to engage the flywheel.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Since large trucks typically use air brakes, the system does double duty, supplying compressed air to the brake system.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Pneumatic starters have the advantages of delivering high torque, mechanical simplicity and reliability.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] They eliminate the need for oversized, heavy storage batteries in prime mover electrical systems.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Large Diesel generators and almost all Diesel engines used as the prime mover of ships use compressed air acting directly on the cylinder head.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] This is not ideal for smaller Diesels, as it provides too much cooling on starting.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Also, the cylinder head needs to have enough space to support an extra valve for the air start system.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The air start system is conceptually very similar to a distributor in a car.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] There is an air distributor that is geared to the camshaft of the Diesel engine; on the top of the air distributor is a single lobe similar to what is found on a camshaft.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Arranged radially around this lobe are roller tip followers for every cylinder.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] When the lobe of the air distributor hits one of the followers it will send an air signal that acts upon the back of the air start valve located in the cylinder head, causing it to open.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Compressed air is provided from a large reservoir that feeds into a header located along the engine.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] As soon as the air start valve is opened, the compressed air is admitted and the engine will begin turning.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] It can be used on two-cycle and four-cycle engines and on reversing engines.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] On large two-stroke engines less than one revolution of the crankshaft is needed for starting.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Some diesel engines from six to 16 cylinders are started by means of a hydraulic motor.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Hydraulic starters and the associated systems provide a sparkless, reliable method of engine starting over a wide temperature range.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Typically hydraulic starters are found in applications such as remote generators, lifeboat propulsion engines, offshore fire pumping engines, and hydraulic fracturing rigs.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The system used to support the hydraulic starter includes valves, pumps, filters, a reservoir, and piston accumulators.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The operator can manually recharge the hydraulic system; this cannot readily be done with electric starting systems, so hydraulic starting systems are favored in applications wherein emergency starting is a requirement.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] With various configurations, Hydraulic starters can be fitted on any engine.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Hydraulic starters employ the high efficiency of the axial piston motor concept, which provides high torque at any temperature or environment, and guarantees minimal wear of the engine ring gear and the pinion.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] A spring starter uses potential energy stored in a spring wound up with a crank to start an engine without a battery or alternator.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Turning the crank moves the pinion into mesh with the engine's ring gear, then winds up the spring.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Pulling the release lever then applies the spring tension to the pinion, turning the ring gear to start the engine.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The pinion automatically disengages from the flywheel after operation.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Provision is also made to allow the engine to be slowly turned over by hand for engine maintenance.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] This is achieved by operating the trip lever just after the pinion has engaged with the flywheel.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Subsequent turning of the winding handle during this operation will not load the starter.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Spring starters can be found in engine-generators and hydraulic power packs, and on lifeboat engines, with the most common application being backup starting system on seagoing vessels.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] A version of this kind of starter called an **impulse** or **wind-up** starter was used on small engines, as used on lawn mowers and other outdoor power equipment, from the 1950s to the early 1970s, when they were taken off the market over safety concerns.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] Some modern gasoline engines with twelve or more cylinders always have at least one or more pistons at the beginning of its power stroke and are able to start by injecting fuel into that cylinder and igniting it.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] The same procedure can be applied to engines with fewer cylinders, if the engine happens to be stopped at the correct position.
[src:barring-engine/engine-starter] This is one way of starting an engine of a car with a stop-start system.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] A **flywheel** is a mechanical device that uses the conservation of angular momentum to store rotational energy, a form of kinetic energy proportional to the product of its moment of inertia and the square of its rotational speed.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] In particular, assuming the flywheel's moment of inertia is constant (i.e., a flywheel with fixed mass and second moment of area revolving about some fixed axis) then the stored (rotational) energy is directly associated with the square of its rotational speed.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] Since a flywheel serves to store mechanical energy for later use, it is natural to consider it as a kinetic energy analogue of an electrical inductor.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] Once suitably abstracted, this shared principle of energy storage is described in the generalized concept of an accumulator.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] As with other types of accumulators, a flywheel inherently smooths sufficiently small deviations in the power output of a system, thereby effectively playing the role of a low-pass filter with respect to the mechanical velocity (angular, or otherwise) of the system.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] More precisely, a flywheel's stored energy will donate a surge in power output upon a drop in power input and will conversely absorb any excess power input (system-generated power) in the form of rotational energy.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] Common uses of a flywheel include smoothing a power output in reciprocating engines, flywheel energy storage, delivering energy at higher rates than the source, and controlling the orientation of a mechanical system using gyroscope and reaction wheel.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] Flywheels are typically made of steel and rotate on conventional bearings; these are generally limited to a maximum revolution rate of a few thousand RPM.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] High energy density flywheels can be made of carbon fiber composites and employ magnetic bearings, enabling them to revolve at speeds up to 60,000 RPM (1 kHz).
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] The principle of the flywheel is found in the Neolithic spindle and the potter's wheel, as well as circular sharpening stones in antiquity.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] In the early 11th century, Ibn Bassal pioneered the use of flywheel in noria and saqiyah.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] The use of the flywheel as a general mechanical device to equalize the speed of rotation is, according to the American medievalist Lynn White, recorded in the *De diversibus artibus* (On various arts) of the German artisan Theophilus Presbyter (ca.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] 1070–1125) who records applying the device in several of his machines.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] In the Industrial Revolution, James Watt contributed to the development of the flywheel in the steam engine, and his contemporary James Pickard used a flywheel combined with a crank to transform reciprocating motion into rotary motion.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] The kinetic energy (or more specifically rotational energy) stored by the flywheel's rotor can be calculated by ${\textstyle {\frac {1}{2}}I\omega ^{2}}$ . ω is the angular velocity, and I is the moment of inertia of the flywheel about its axis of symmetry.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] The moment of inertia is a measure of resistance to torque applied on a spinning object (i.e. the higher the moment of inertia, the slower it will accelerate when a given torque is applied).
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] The moment of inertia can be calculated for cylindrical shapes using mass ( ${\textstyle m}$ ) and radius ( r ).
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] For a given flywheel design, the kinetic energy is proportional to the ratio of the hoop stress to the material density and to the mass.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] The specific tensile strength of a flywheel can be defined as ${\textstyle {\frac {\sigma _{t}}{\rho }}}$ .
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] The flywheel material with the highest specific tensile strength will yield the highest energy storage per unit mass.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] This is one reason why carbon fiber is a material of interest.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] For a given design the stored energy is proportional to the hoop stress and the volume.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] An electric motor-powered flywheel is common in practice.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] The output power of the electric motor is approximately equal to the output power of the flywheel.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] It can be calculated by ${\textstyle (V_{i})(V_{t})\left({\frac {\sin(\delta )}{X_{S}}}\right)}$ , where $V_{i}$ is the voltage of rotor winding, $V_{t}$ is stator voltage, and $\delta$ is the angle between two voltages.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] Increasing amounts of rotation energy can be stored in the flywheel until the rotor shatters.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] This happens when the hoop stress within the rotor exceeds the ultimate tensile strength of the rotor material.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] Tensile stress can be calculated by $\rho r^{2}\omega ^{2}$ , where $\rho$ is the density of the cylinder, r is the radius of the cylinder, and $\omega$ is the angular velocity of the cylinder.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] A rimmed flywheel has a rim, a hub, and spokes.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] Calculation of the flywheel's moment of inertia can be more easily analysed by applying various simplifications.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] One method is to assume the spokes, shaft and hub have zero moments of inertia, and the flywheel's moment of inertia is from the rim alone.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] Another is to lump moments of inertia of spokes, hub and shaft into the rim.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] These may be estimated as a percentage of the flywheel's moment of inertia, with the majority from the rim, so that $I_{\mathrm {rim} }=KI_{\mathrm {flywheel} }$ .
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] For example, if the moments of inertia of hub, spokes and shaft are deemed negligible, and the rim's thickness is very small compared to its mean radius ( R ), the radius of rotation of the rim is equal to its mean radius and thus ${\textstyle I_{\mathrm {rim} }=M_{\mathrm {rim} }R^{2}}$ .
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] A shaftless flywheel eliminates the annulus holes, shaft or hub.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] It has higher energy density than conventional design but requires a specialized magnetic bearing and control system.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] The specific energy of a flywheel is determined by ${\textstyle {\frac {E}{M}}=K{\frac {\sigma }{\rho }}}$ , in which K is the shape factor, $\sigma$ the material's tensile strength and $\rho$ the density.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] While a typical flywheel has a shape factor of 0.3, the shaftless flywheel has a shape factor close to 0.6, out of a theoretical limit of about 1.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] A superflywheel consists of a solid core (hub) and multiple thin layers of high-strength flexible materials (such as special steels, carbon fiber composites, glass fiber, or graphene) wound around it.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] Compared to conventional flywheels, superflywheels can store more energy and are safer to operate.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] In case of failure, a superflywheel does not explode or burst into large shards like a regular flywheel, but instead splits into layers.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] The separated layers then slow a superflywheel down by sliding against the inner walls of the enclosure, thus preventing any further destruction.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] Although the exact value of energy density of a superflywheel would depend on the material used, it could theoretically be as high as 1200 Wh (4.4 MJ) per kg of mass for graphene superflywheels.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] The first superflywheel was patented in 1964 by the Soviet-Russian scientist Nurbei Guilia.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] Flywheels are made from many different materials; the application determines the choice of material.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] Small flywheels made of lead are found in children's toys.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] Cast iron flywheels are used in old steam engines.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] Flywheels used in car engines are made of cast or nodular iron, steel or aluminum.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] Flywheels made from high-strength steel or composites have been proposed for use in vehicle energy storage and braking systems.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] The efficiency of a flywheel is determined by the maximum amount of energy it can store per unit weight.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] As the flywheel's rotational speed or angular velocity is increased, the stored energy increases; however, the stresses also increase.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] If the hoop stress surpass the tensile strength of the material, the flywheel will break apart.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] Thus, the tensile strength limits the amount of energy that a flywheel can store.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] In this context, using lead for a flywheel in a child's toy is not efficient; however, the flywheel velocity never approaches its burst velocity because the limit in this case is the pulling-power of the child.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] In other applications, such as an automobile, the flywheel operates at a specified angular velocity and is constrained by the space it must fit in, so the goal is to maximize the stored energy per unit volume.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] The material selection therefore depends on the application.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] Flywheels are often used to provide continuous power output in systems where the energy source is not continuous.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] For example, a flywheel is used to smooth the fast angular velocity fluctuations of the crankshaft in a reciprocating engine.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] In this case, a crankshaft flywheel stores energy when torque is exerted on it by a firing piston and then returns that energy to the piston to compress a fresh charge of air and fuel.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] Another example is the friction motor which powers devices such as toy cars.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] In unstressed and inexpensive cases, to save on cost, the bulk of the mass of the flywheel is toward the rim of the wheel.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] Pushing the mass away from the axis of rotation heightens rotational inertia for a given total mass.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] A flywheel may also be used to supply intermittent pulses of energy at power levels that exceed the abilities of its energy source.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] This is achieved by accumulating energy in the flywheel over a period of time, at a rate that is compatible with the energy source, and then releasing energy at a much higher rate over a relatively short time when it is needed.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] For example, flywheels are used in power hammers and riveting machines.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] Flywheels can be used to control direction and oppose unwanted motions.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] Flywheels in this context have a wide range of applications: gyroscopes for instrumentation, ship stability, satellite stabilization (reaction wheel), keeping a toy spin spinning (friction motor), stabilizing magnetically-levitated objects (spin-stabilized magnetic levitation).
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] Flywheels may also be used as an electric compensator, like a synchronous compensator, that can either produce or sink reactive power but would not affect the real power.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] The purposes for that application are to improve the power factor of the system or adjust the grid voltage.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] Typically, the flywheels used in this field are similar in structure and installation as the synchronous motor (but it is called synchronous compensator or synchronous condenser in this context).
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] There are also some other kinds of compensator using flywheels, like the single phase induction machine.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] But the basic ideas here are the same, the flywheels are controlled to spin exactly at the frequency which you want to compensate.
[src:barring-engine/flywheel] For a synchronous compensator, the voltage of rotor and stator also must be kept in phase, which is the same as keeping the magnetic field of rotor and the total magnetic field in phase (in the rotating frame reference).
[src:barring-engine/jacking-gear] A **jacking gear** (also known as a **turning gear** or **barring gear**) is a device placed on the main shaft of an engine or the rotor of a turbine.
[src:barring-engine/jacking-gear] The jacking gear rotates the shaft or rotor and associated machinery (such as reduction gears and main steam or gas turbines), to ensure uniform cool-down.
[src:barring-engine/jacking-gear] Without turning, hogging or sagging can occur.
[src:barring-engine/jacking-gear] Additionally, the jacking gear's assistance in rotation can be used when inspecting the shaft, reduction gears, bearings, and turbines.
[src:barring-engine/jacking-gear] As an auxiliary function, the jacking gear also helps to maintain a protective oil membrane at all shaft journal bearings.
[src:barring-engine/jacking-gear] Hogging is when the shaft bows upwards due to thermal stratification.
[src:barring-engine/jacking-gear] On the engine shaft of a marine vessel, this process also prevents the shaft from warping when a ship is preparing to achieve maneuvering status.
[src:barring-engine/jacking-gear] The jacking gear motor is generally designed to rotate the shaft at approximately 1/10 rpm.
[src:barring-engine/jacking-gear] Most jacking gear motors are rated at 5 hp.
[src:barring-engine/jacking-gear] The jacking gear motor assembly applies power and torque to the reduction gear by a flexible coupling or clutch that can freely engage and disengage to the high-pressure pinion (driving gear).
[src:barring-engine/jacking-gear] Engaging is accomplished by means of a simple lever.
[src:barring-engine/jacking-gear] Some newer propulsion arrangements utilize an automatic control system located in the engine room.
[src:barring-engine/jacking-gear] Jacking gears often feature a lock to prevent the shaft from turning during current or tide changes or when being towed.
[src:barring-engine/jacking-gear] But some industrial gas turbines (GE Frame 5 and Frame 6 types) use a jacking system in which two hydraulic cylinders rotates the shaft about 1/4 turn in one or two seconds every 30 seconds.
[src:barring-engine/jacking-gear] GE Frame 9B gas turbines, in which accessories were designed in beginning of 1970's by Alstom Belfort engineering, use a high pressure hydraulic motor which connects to the main shaft through an automatic SSS Clutch.
[src:barring-engine/jacking-gear] Turning speed was chosen about 6 RPM, because the resisting torque is the smallest at this speed, then requiring a very low power.
